00:21:15.440 --> 00:21:16.300
Winter is coming.

00:21:16.400 --> 00:21:16.620
Why?

00:21:17.120 --> 00:21:20.140
Well, because PEP 814 is frozen dict.

00:21:22.680 --> 00:21:23.860
That was a bad joke.

00:21:24.360 --> 00:21:28.260
No, it was, it was so bad it was good, I think.

00:21:28.340 --> 00:21:28.680
No, anyway.

00:21:28.680 --> 00:21:33.580
The idea is that we've got frozen set.

00:21:33.740 --> 00:21:38.100
We've got other types of frozen item, containers and data structures.

00:21:38.260 --> 00:21:40.120
But we didn't have frozen dictionary.

00:21:40.420 --> 00:21:43.740
So the idea is, it's a read only, right?

00:21:43.800 --> 00:21:44.640
So you create a thing.

00:21:45.160 --> 00:21:52.760
You want to be able to return it from a function or share it and have an absolute guarantee that people are not changing it, right?

00:21:52.840 --> 00:21:55.220
Adding or moving items, keys, and so on.

00:21:55.220 --> 00:22:00.440
And I don't think that really applies to stuff referenced in there.

00:22:00.500 --> 00:22:05.920
So if you put a list as a value and then you go and like get the point of the list, you probably can still change it.

00:22:05.960 --> 00:22:07.800
But, you know, like, I guess it depends.

00:22:08.120 --> 00:22:11.280
If you fill it with only other frozen stuff, it's frozen all the way down.

00:22:12.480 --> 00:22:14.960
But it's really cool because it allows better concurrency.

00:22:15.300 --> 00:22:21.940
This is something we're going to be paying more attention to in the future as Python T starts, you know, free thread of Python starts to become a thing.

00:22:21.940 --> 00:22:25.460
You're like, well, I hate all this locking we have to do in these race conditions.

00:22:25.460 --> 00:22:28.440
Like, well, if you can't change it, you don't need to lock on it.

00:22:28.500 --> 00:22:28.980
You know what I mean?

00:22:29.480 --> 00:22:30.500
So that's very cool.

00:22:30.600 --> 00:22:34.800
I don't want to add any more than that, but it will be in Python 3.15.

